First, define the matrix \emph{C} and the vector \textbf{\emph{c}}

\texttt{~~~C={[}-4,~-2;~-2,~1;~0,~1{]};}\\\texttt{~~~c={[}2;~2;~1{]};}

Then solve the least squares equation \emph{C\textbf{s} = \textbf{c}}
for \textbf{\emph{s}}

\texttt{~~~s=(C'*C)\textbackslash{}(C'*c);~~\%~or~s=inv(C'*C)*C'*c;}

Finally, from \textbf{\emph{s}} we retrieve the coefficient vector
\textbf{\emph{a}}

\texttt{~~~a\_1~=~{[}1;~-3;~0;~0{]};}\\\texttt{~~~a\_2~=~{[}0;~0;~0;~1{]};}\\\texttt{~~~a~=~s(1)*a\_1~+~s(2)*a\_2;}

This determines the function \emph{p(x)}

\texttt{~~~p~=~@(x)~a(1)*x\^{}3~+~a(2)*x\^{}2~+~a(3)*x~+~a(4);}

All that is left now is to plot the points \emph{(0, 1)}, \emph{(1, 2)}
and \emph{(2,2)} as well as the polynomial \emph{p(x)} on the interval
\emph{{[}0, 2{]}}:

\texttt{~~~hold~on}\\\texttt{~~~plot(0,~1,~'o')}\\\texttt{~~~plot(1,~2,~'o')}\\\texttt{~~~plot(2,~2,~'o')}\\\texttt{~~~fplot(p,~{[}0,~2{]})~~\%~or~eg~plot(linspace(0,~2),~p(linspace(0,~2)))}
